<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-03-06T18:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-03-06T18:00:00-05:00" n="718" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d718">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 652.119/623</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Page</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-03-06T23:00:00+00:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">March 6, 1918, 11 p.m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received</hi> (<hi rend="italic">March
                                        7?</hi>) <hi rend="italic">3.33 p.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>8923. Your 6771 [<hi rend="italic">6772</hi>], March 5, 6 p.m. I
                                discussed this matter today with <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_CLR1">Lord Robert Cecil</persName>
                                who assures me that the only interest the British Government had in
                                postponing the conclusion of negotiations was to bring up the
                                question of Spanish shipping before they were finished in order to
                                exercise pressure on Spain to release all the tonnage possible for
                                Allied needs. Now that the British Government is informed that it is
                                too late to do this since both the French and American agreements
                                are ready for ratification, <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_CLR1">Cecil</persName> informs me
                                that Lord <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_RERDI1">Reading</persName> has been instructed by telegraph to ask you
                                to do what you can to obtain the Spanish tonnage in some other
                                way.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1">
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Page</hi>
                                    </persName>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>